ClinVarSubmissionID.title: TMEM94, 1-BP DUP, NT2635_INTELLECTUAL DEVELOPMENTAL DISORDER WITH CARDIAC DEFECTS AND DYSMORPHIC FACIES

ObservedData.Attribute: In a 17-year-old boy, born of unrelated European American parents (family 3), with intellectual developmental disorder with cardiac defects and dysmorphic facies (IDDCDF; 618316), Stephen et al. (2018) identified compound heterozygous mutations in the TMEM94 gene: a 1-bp duplication (c.2635dup, NM_001321148.1), resulting in a frameshift and premature termination (Met879AsnfsTer18), and a G-to-C transversion in intron 6 (c.795-1G-C; 618163.0004), resulting in a splice site defect. Analysis of patient cells showed that the splice site mutation caused 2 mutant transcripts, both of which were predicted to result in a frameshift and premature termination (Trp266ProfsTer30 and Arg265SerfsTer7). The mutations were found by whole-genome sequencing and confirmed by Sanger sequencing. The c.2635dup mutation was inherited from the unaffected mother; DNA from the father was unavailable. Patient fibroblasts showed an 85 to 90% reduction in TMEM94 gene expression compared to controls.
